es, got arrested in support of Sacco and Vanzetti, raised money for workers' cooperatives and leftist journalism, and demonstrated against nuclear weapons and in support of fair housing, the Rosenbergs, and civil rights. This biography welcomes Gold back into cultural conversations about art, literature, politics, social change, and Jewish American life in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral Interest : Biography. 4aHistory : Radical History. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848099240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480992423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480992/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles